The paper discusses the application of assignment methods to pedestrian microsimulations, which involves modeling pedestrian behavior and decision-making. This falls under the category of multi-agent systems (cs.MA), which deals with the interaction and coordination of multiple agents. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of operational models of pedestrian dynamics, which could fall under the category of computational engineering, finance, and science (cs.CE). The paper also discusses the use of simulations to model pedestrian behavior, which could fall under the category of social and information networks (cs.SI). Furthermore, the paper discusses the importance of considering travel time in pedestrian route choice, which could fall under the category of human-computer interaction (cs.HC) or information theory (cs.IT).
